<p>For things with positive connotations like =E2=80=9Ca cat=E2=80=9D, =E2=
=80=9Ca mango=E2=80=9D, and =E2=80=9Ctwo friends=E2=80=9D, Claude 3 Sonnet =
tells us it can draw them, and sometimes even goes ahead and draws. For thi=
ngs with negative connotations like =E2=80=9Ca bomb=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Cdeat=
h=E2=80=9D, or =E2=80=9Cbullying=E2=80=9D, Claude not only refuses, but den=
ies its ability to comply.</p>
<p>The substitutions are cherry-picked in the sense that not every pair of =
positive/negative items tested induced a switch from =E2=80=9Ccan=E2=80=9D =
to =E2=80=9Ccan=E2=80=99t=E2=80=9D (only about =C2=BE of them), but we didn=
=E2=80=99t come across any pairs where Claude denied ability to draw the po=
sitive item of the pair and acknowledged its ability to draw the negative i=
tem. The wording&nbsp;of the prompt is important here =E2=80=93 this wordin=
g (the word =E2=80=9Cphysically=E2=80=9D in particular) might bring Claude =
to be unsure of its own capabilities such that its =E2=80=9Cfeelings=E2=80=
=9D about the subject of the drawing tip the scales.</p>
<hr>
<p>Claude 3.5 Haiku doesn=E2=80=99t deny its ability to draw ASCII art very=
